# dry-refactoring-plan-assumption-audit — History

## v2.2.0 (2026-06-30)

**Changed by:** ProjectHephaestus issue #1439 planning turn (collapse explicit phase-runner shim methods in `hephaestus/automation/implementer.py` into existing `__getattr__` delegation).
**Verification:** unverified — planning-only. No pytest/ruff/mypy executed against the repo change; only a 12-line Python semantics-probe snippet was run (it validates `patch.object` vs `__getattr__`, NOT the #1439 refactor).

### What changed
- Added a NEW failure mode (minor bump): **the issue's PROPOSED MECHANISM can itself be stale**, not just its evidence/counts. Issue #1439 proposed inventing `__getattr__` forwarding + a delegate frozenset that a PRIOR PR (#714/#597) had already built; the real work was EXTENDING it to the ~18 remaining explicit shims (the "25" count was stale; actual 18).
- Added a "When to Use" trigger: planning a refactor whose proposed mechanism may already exist in the target module.
- Added 3 new Failed Attempts rows: stale proposed mechanism; unverified mypy/import-orphan claim after deleting typed shims; scoping out the high-risk half (second coordinator class) with grep-counted back-reference coupling rather than assertion.
- Added a planning-only `## Issue #1439 Specific Findings (planning-only — unverified)` subsection and Quick Reference greps (`grep -n "__getattr__\|DELEGATE\|_LAZY\|frozenset" target.py`).
- All #1439 content is marked `unverified — planning-only`; the skill's top-level verification stays `unverified` (unchanged).

### Why
The prior versions (v1.0.0–v2.1.0) captured stale *evidence/counts* and shim-layer pitfalls. #1439 surfaced a distinct trap: a refactoring issue can ask you to BUILD a mechanism that already exists from an earlier refactor, so the plan must grep the target for the proposed mechanism before designing it, and must decline the bundled high-risk half (a second coordinator) with quantified coupling evidence.

